Message.Title: If you've ever been in trouble for sleeping on the job, take heart: you can still achieve upward mobility in a local union.
Message.Msg: Take, for instance, Mark Rosenthal, the president of Local 983 of District Council 37 in New York. Rosenthal makes $156,000 a year and apparently spends only two hours a day at work--much of that napping, according to his colleagues who spoke out to the New York Post. Marvin Robbins, a union vice president, paints an unflattering portrait of his boss's routine: "He eats lunch when he arrives at work at 2 p.m. Then, like clockwork, he goes to sleep with a cup of soda on the table and the straw in it. Then he wakes up, looks at his watch and says, 'I have to get out before the traffic gets bad.' He's usually out by 4 p.m. after being at the office two hours." The Post describes Local 983 as "the city's largest blue-collar municipal workers union." Rosenthal promised to fight corruption when he ran for its presidency in the late '90s. However, union officials allege he has abused his position to get many a free lunch. They estimate he expenses $1,400 a month on food, much of it from catered events and meals he claims are for "union business." Rosenthal asserted to the Post that he works "12-to-14-hour days," and he claims these complaints are coming from supporters of his challenger as he faces reelection in early June. He offered two more explanations: first, that executives often take "power naps," and second, that his naps are caused by pain pills he was prescribed after falling through a chair last year while eating at McDonald's. "The chair broke because I'm big," Rosenthal argued. "I'm 60 years old, so if I eat during my lunch hour and take a little medication, can't I close my eyes? Is it so outrageous?"

Cisco has been a great story for the investors, and now the dividends are adding another good reason to own the stock. The next level to watch could be $27, if it crosses $25. Thereafter, one can hope for $30, but that is currently a very long shot. In any case, the stock is likely to remain positive for some time, unless the market corrects significantly. Earnings are likely to be the next major trigger. Now the expectations will be higher, and slippages may not be that welcome. So it will be relatively risky to take that exposure. It will be better if one can step aside before the earnings. Of course, the long term investors will like to remain with the company and that strategy will most likely work. Meanwhile Cisco continued with acquisition of small companies to further its business interests. The changing segment focus has been visible. Technological innovation remains the key, and Cisco has to continue creating new products and services which will strengthen its IPR portfolio. Patents are huge assets now and companies are extremely active in monetizing their value. Cisco has already faced patent infringement lawsuits recently, like the one filed by VirnetX where it got a favorable ruling. Even small companies are filing multi-billion dollar lawsuits. MGT Capital Investments (MGT) recently filed a huge lawsuit against casino gaming companies. So Cisco is likely to remain strong till the next major event or any major news flow (or a correction in the market). Currently it does make sense to tag along with a little bit of caution.
